# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arp-spoofing-defense
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The **Address Resolution Protocol** (**ARP**) is a communication protocol for discovering the link layer address, such as a MAC address, associated with an internet layer address, typically an IPv4 address.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The protocol, part of the Internet protocol suite, was defined in 1982 by RFC 826, which is Internet Standard STD 37.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] ARP enables a host to send, for example, an IPv4 packet to another node in the local network by providing a protocol to get the MAC address associated with an IP address.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The host broadcasts a request containing the target node's IP address, and the node with that IP address replies with its MAC address.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] ARP has been implemented with many combinations of network and data link layer technologies, such as IPv4, Chaosnet, DECnet and Xerox PARC Universal Packet (PUP) using IEEE 802 standards, FDDI, X.25, Frame Relay and Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM).
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] In Internet Protocol Version 6 (IPv6) networks, the functionality of ARP is provided by the Neighbor Discovery Protocol (NDP).
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The Address Resolution Protocol is a request–response protocol.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Its messages are directly encapsulated by a link-layer protocol.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] It is communicated within the boundaries of a single subnetwork and is never routed.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The Address Resolution Protocol uses a simple message format containing one address resolution request or response.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The packets are carried at the data link layer of the underlying network as raw payload.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] In the case of Ethernet, a 0x0806 EtherType value is used to identify ARP frames.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The size of the ARP message depends on the link layer and network layer address sizes.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The message header specifies the types of network in use at each layer as well as the size of addresses of each.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The message header is completed with the operation code for request (1) and reply (2).
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The payload of the packet consists of four addresses: the hardware and protocol addresses of the sender and receiver hosts.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The principal packet structure of ARP packets is shown in the following table, which illustrates the case of IPv4 networks running on Ethernet.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] In this scenario, the packet has 48-bit fields for the sender hardware address (SHA) and target hardware address (THA), and 32-bit fields for the corresponding sender and target protocol addresses (SPA and TPA).
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The ARP packet size in this case is 28 bytes.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] This field specifies the network link protocol type.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] This field specifies the internetwork protocol for which the ARP request is intended.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Length (in octets) of internetwork addresses.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The internetwork protocol is specified in PTYPE.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Specifies the operation that the sender is performing: 1 for request, 2 for reply.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] In an ARP request, this field is used to indicate the address of the host sending the request.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] In an ARP reply, this field is used to indicate the address of the host that the request was looking for.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] In an ARP request, this field is ignored.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] In an ARP reply this field is used to indicate the address of the host that originated the ARP request.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Internetwork address of the intended receiver.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] ARP parameter values have been standardized and are maintained by the Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA).
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] This appears in the Ethernet frame header when the payload is an ARP packet and is not to be confused with PTYPE, which appears within this encapsulated ARP packet.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] ARP's placement within the Internet protocol suite and the OSI model may be a matter of confusion or even of dispute.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] RFC 826 places it into the link layer and characterizes it as a tool to inquire about the "higher level layer", such as the Internet layer.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] RFC 1122 also discusses ARP in its link layer section.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Richard Stevens places ARP in the OSI's data link layer while newer editions associate it with the network layer or introduce an intermediate OSI layer 2.5.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Two computers, *A* and *B*, are connected to the same local area network with no intervening gateway or router.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] *A* has a packet to send to IP address *192.168.0.55* which happens to be the address of *B*.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Before sending the packet to *B*, *A* broadcasts an ARP request message – addressed with the broadcast MAC address *FF:FF:FF:FF:FF:FF* and requesting response from the node with IP address *192.168.0.55*.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] All nodes of the network receive the message, but only *B* replies since it has the requested IP address.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] *B* responds with an ARP response message containing its MAC addresses which *A* receives.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] *A* sends the data packet on the link addressed with *B*'s MAC address.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Typically, a network node maintains a lookup cache that associates IP and MAC addresses.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] In this example, if *A* had the lookup cached, then it would not need to broadcast the ARP request.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Also, when *B* received the request, it could cache the lookup to *A* so that if *B* needs to send a packet to *A* later, it does not need to use ARP to look up its MAC address.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Finally, when *A* receives the ARP response, it can cache the lookup for future messages addressed to the same IP address.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] An **ARP probe** in IPv4 is an ARP request constructed with the SHA of the probing host, an SPA of all 0s, a THA of all 0s, and a TPA set to the IPv4 address being probed for.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] If some host on the network regards the IPv4 address (in the TPA) as its own, it will reply to the probe (via the SHA of the probing host) thus informing the probing host of the address conflict.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] If instead there is no host that regards the IPv4 address as its own, then there will be no reply.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] When several such probes have been sent, with slight delays, and none receive replies, it can reasonably be expected that no conflict exists.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] As the original probe packet contains neither a valid SHA/SPA nor a valid THA/TPA pair, there is no risk of any host using the packet to update its cache with problematic data.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Before beginning to use an IPv4 address (whether received from manual configuration, DHCP, or some other means), a host implementing this specification must test to see if the address is already in use, by broadcasting ARP probe packets.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] ARP may also be used as a simple announcement protocol.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] This is useful for updating other hosts' mappings of a hardware address when the sender's IP address or MAC address changes.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Such an announcement, also called a **gratuitous ARP** (**GARP**) message, is usually broadcast as an *ARP request* containing the SPA in the target field (TPA=SPA), with THA set to zero.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] An alternative way is to broadcast an *ARP reply* with the sender's SHA and SPA duplicated in the target fields (TPA=SPA, THA=SHA).
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The *ARP request* and *ARP reply* announcements are both standards-based methods, but the *ARP request* method is preferred.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Some devices may be configured for the use of either of these two types of announcements.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] An ARP announcement is not intended to solicit a reply; instead, it updates any cached entries in the ARP tables of other hosts that receive the packet.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The operation code in the announcement may be either request or reply; the ARP standard specifies that the opcode is only processed after the ARP table has been updated from the address fields.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Many operating systems issue an ARP announcement during startup.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] This helps to resolve problems that would otherwise occur if, for example, a network card was recently changed (changing the IP-address-to-MAC-address mapping) and other hosts still have the old mapping in their ARP caches.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] ARP announcements are also used by some network interfaces to provide load balancing for incoming traffic.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] In a team of network cards, it is used to announce a different MAC address within the team that should receive incoming packets.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] ARP announcements can be used in the Zeroconf protocol to allow automatic assignment of a link-local address to an interface where no other IP address configuration is available.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The announcements are used to ensure an address chosen by a host is not in use by other hosts on the network link.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] InARP is primarily used in Frame Relay (DLCI) and ATM networks, in which layer-2 addresses of virtual circuits are sometimes obtained from layer-2 signaling, and the corresponding layer-3 addresses must be available before those virtual circuits can be used.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The Reverse Address Resolution Protocol (Reverse ARP or RARP), like InARP, translates layer-2 addresses to layer-3 addresses.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] However, in InARP, the requesting station queries the layer-3 address of another node, whereas RARP is used to obtain the layer-3 address of the requesting station itself for address configuration purposes.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] RARP is obsolete; it was replaced by BOOTP, which was later superseded by the Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP).
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Because ARP does not provide methods for authenticating ARP replies on a network, ARP replies can come from systems other than the one with the required Layer 2 address.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] An ARP *proxy* is a system that answers the ARP request on behalf of another system for which it will forward traffic, normally as a part of the network's design, such as for a dial-up internet service.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] By contrast, in ARP *spoofing* the answering system, or *spoofer*, replies to a request for another system's address with the aim of intercepting data bound for that system.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] A malicious user may use ARP spoofing to perform a man-in-the-middle or denial-of-service attack on other users on the network.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Various software exists to both detect and perform ARP spoofing attacks, though ARP itself does not provide any methods of protection from such attacks.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Computers may maintain lists of known addresses, rather than using an active protocol.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] In this method, each computer maintains a database of the mapping of Layer 3 addresses (e.g., IP addresses) to Layer 2 addresses (e.g., Ethernet MAC addresses).
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] This data is maintained primarily by interpreting ARP packets from the local network link.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Thus, it is often called the *ARP cache*.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Since at least the 1980s, networked computers have a utility called *arp* for interrogating or manipulating this database.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Historically, other methods were used to maintain the mapping between addresses, such as static configuration files, or centrally maintained lists.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Embedded systems such as networked cameras and networked power distribution devices, which lack a user interface, can use so-called *ARP stuffing* to make an initial network connection, although this is a misnomer, as ARP is not involved.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The computer sends special packets to the device, typically a ping packet with a non-default size.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] The user then communicates with it by telnet or web protocols to complete the configuration.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/address-resolution-protocol] Such devices typically have a method to disable this process once the device is operating normally, as the capability can make it vulnerable to attack.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] In computer networking, **ARP spoofing** (also **ARP cache poisoning** or **ARP poison routing**) is a technique by which an attacker sends (spoofed) Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) messages onto a local area network.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] Generally, the aim is to associate the attacker's MAC address with the IP address of another host, such as the default gateway, causing any traffic meant for that IP address to be sent to the attacker instead.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] ARP spoofing may allow an attacker to intercept data frames on a network, modify the traffic, or stop all traffic.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] Often, the attack is used as an opening for other attacks, such as denial of service, man in the middle, or session hijacking attacks.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] The attack can only be used on networks that use ARP, and requires the attacker to have direct access to the local network segment to be attacked.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] The Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) is a widely used communications protocol for resolving internet layer addresses into link layer addresses.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] When an Internet Protocol (IP) datagram is sent from one host to another in a local area network, the destination IP address must be resolved to a MAC address for transmission via the data link layer.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] The first host sends a broadcast packet on the local network.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] This packet is known as an *ARP request*.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] The second host with the IP in the ARP request then responds with a broadcast *ARP reply* that contains the MAC address associated with its IP.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] Network hosts will automatically cache any ARP replies they receive, regardless of which or any network hosts requested them.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] Even ARP entries that have not yet expired in the cache will be overwritten when a new ARP reply packet is received.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] There is no method in the ARP protocol by which a host can authenticate the peer from which the packet originated.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] This behavior is the vulnerability that allows ARP spoofing to occur.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] The basic principle behind ARP spoofing is to exploit the lack of authentication in the ARP protocol by sending spoofed ARP messages onto the LAN.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] ARP spoofing attacks can be run from a compromised host on the LAN or from an attacker's machine that is connected directly to the target LAN.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] Generally, the goal of the attack is to associate the attacker's host MAC address with the IP address of a target host, so that any traffic meant for the target host will be sent to the attacker's host.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] The simplest form of certification is the use of static, read-only entries for critical services in the ARP cache of a host.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] Hosts don't need to transmit ARP requests where such entries exist.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] While static entries provide some security against spoofing, they increase maintenance effort as address mappings for all systems in the network must be generated and distributed.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] Software that detects ARP spoofing generally relies on some form of certification or cross-checking of ARP responses.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] Uncertified ARP responses are then blocked.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] These techniques may be integrated with the DHCP server so that both dynamic and static IP addresses are certified.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] This capability may be implemented in individual hosts or may be integrated into Ethernet switches or other network equipment.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] The existence of multiple IP addresses associated with a single MAC address may indicate an ARP spoof attack, although there are legitimate uses of such a configuration.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] In a more passive approach, a device listens for ARP replies on a network and sends a notification via email when an ARP entry changes.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] AntiARP also provides Windows-based spoofing prevention at the kernel level.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] ArpStar is a Linux module for kernel 2.6 and Linksys routers that drops invalid packets that violate mapping.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] Some virtualized environments, such as the Kernel-based Virtual Machine, provide security mechanisms to prevent MAC spoofing between guests running on the same host.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] Some Ethernet adapters provide MAC and VLAN anti-spoofing features.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] OpenBSD watches passively for hosts impersonating the local host and notifies in case of any attempt to overwrite a permanent entry.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] Linux ignores unsolicited replies, but, on the other hand, uses responses to requests from other machines to update its cache.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] Solaris accepts updates on entries only after a timeout.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] In Microsoft Windows, the behavior of the ARP cache can be configured through several registry entries under HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Services\Tcpip\Parameters, ArpCacheLife, ArpCacheMinReferenceLife, ArpUseEtherSNAP, ArpTRSingleRoute, ArpAlwaysSourceRoute, ArpRetryCount.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] The techniques that are used in ARP spoofing can also be used to implement redundancy of network services.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] For example, some software allows a backup server to issue a gratuitous ARP request in order to take over for a defective server and transparently offer redundancy.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] Circle and CUJO are two companies that have commercialized products centered around this strategy.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] ARP spoofing is often used by developers to debug IP traffic between two hosts when a switch is in use: if host A and host B are communicating through an Ethernet switch, their traffic would normally be invisible to a third monitoring host M.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] The developer configures A to have M's MAC address for B, and B to have M's MAC address for A; and also configures M to forward packets.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/arp-spoofing] M can now monitor the traffic, exactly as in a man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/dhcp-snooping] In computer networking, **DHCP snooping** is a series of techniques applied to improve the security of a Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP) infrastructure.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/dhcp-snooping] DHCP servers allocate IP addresses to clients on a LAN.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/dhcp-snooping] DHCP snooping can be configured on LAN switches to exclude rogue DHCP servers and remove malicious or malformed DHCP traffic.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/dhcp-snooping] In addition, information on hosts which have successfully completed a DHCP transaction is accrued in a database of *bindings* which may then be used by other security or accounting features.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/dhcp-snooping] Other features may use DHCP snooping database information to ensure IP integrity on a Layer 2 switched domain.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/dynamic-arp-inspection] The Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) has many security issues.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/dynamic-arp-inspection] These include the Man In The Middle (MITM) attack through the ARP spoofing, ARP cache poisoning, Denial of Service and ARP poison routing attacks.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/dynamic-arp-inspection] ArpON is a host-based solution that makes the ARP secure and avoids the man-in-the-middle attack through ARP spoofing, ARP cache poisoning or ARP poison routing.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/dynamic-arp-inspection] The goal of ArpON is therefore to provide a secure and efficient network daemon that provides the SARPI, DARPI and HARPI anti-ARP-spoofing technique, thus making the ARP standardized protocol secure from any foreign intrusion.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] In computer networking, **IP address spoofing** or **IP spoofing** is the creation of Internet Protocol (IP) packets with a false source IP address, for the purpose of impersonating another computing system.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] The basic protocol for sending data over the Internet and many other computer networks is the Internet Protocol (IP).
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] The protocol specifies that each IP packet must have a header which contains (among other things) the IP address of the sender of the packet.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] The source IP address is normally the address that the packet was sent from, but the sender's address in the header can be altered, so that to the recipient it appears that the packet came from another source.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] The protocol requires the receiving computer to send back a response to the source IP address; therefore, spoofing is mainly used when the sender can anticipate the network response or does not care about the response.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] The source IP address provides only limited information about the sender.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] It may provide general information on the region, city and town from which the packet was sent.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] It does not provide information on the identity of the sender or the computer being used.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] IP address spoofing involving the use of a trusted IP address can be used by network intruders to overcome network security measures, such as authentication based on IP addresses.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] This type of attack is most effective where trust relationships exist between machines.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] For example, it is common on some corporate networks to have internal systems trust each other, so that users can log in without a username or password, provided they are connecting from another machine on the internal network, which would require them to be already logged in.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] By spoofing a connection from a trusted machine, an attacker on the same network may be able to access the target machine without authentication.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] IP address spoofing is most frequently used in denial-of-service attacks, where the objective is to flood the target with an overwhelming volume of traffic, and the attacker does not care about receiving responses to the attack packets.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Packets with spoofed IP addresses are more difficult to filter since each spoofed packet appears to come from a different address, and they hide the true source of the attack.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Denial-of-service attacks that use spoofing typically randomly choose addresses from the entire IP address space, though more sophisticated spoofing mechanisms might avoid non-routable addresses or unused portions of the IP address space.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] In DDoS attacks, the attacker may decide to spoof the IP source address to randomly generated addresses, so the victim machine cannot distinguish between the spoofed packets and legitimate packets.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] The replies would then be sent to random addresses that do not end up anywhere in particular.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Such packages-to-nowhere are called the backscatter, and there are network telescopes monitoring backscatter to measure the statistical intensity of DDoS attacks on the internet over time.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] IP address spoofing is a prerequisite for *reflection* attacks, in which the attacker sends requests with the victim's IP address as the spoofed source to third-party servers, which then send responses to the victim.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] When the response is substantially larger than the request, the technique is known as an *amplification* attack.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Protocols historically abused for amplification include DNS, NTP, SSDP, and memcached.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] The use of packets with a false source IP address is not always evidence of malicious intent.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] For example, in performance testing of websites, hundreds or even thousands of "vusers" (virtual users) may be created, each executing a test script against the website under test, in order to simulate what will happen when the system goes "live" and a large number of users log in simultaneously.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Since each user will normally have its own IP address, commercial testing products (such as HP LoadRunner, WebLOAD, and others) can use IP spoofing, allowing each user its own "return address" as well.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] IP spoofing is also used in some server-side load balancing.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] It lets the load balancer spray incoming traffic, but not need to be in the return path from the servers to the client.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] This saves a networking hop through switches and the load balancer as well as outbound message processing load on the load balancer.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Output usually has more packets and bytes, so the savings are significant.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Network services that authenticate clients solely by source IP address are inherently vulnerable to spoofing.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Historical examples include the Berkeley r-commands suite (rlogin, rsh, rcp), which are now largely deprecated in favour of SSH.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Some remote procedure call implementations and any application relying on IP-based access control lists without cryptographic authentication remain susceptible.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Packet filtering is one defense against IP spoofing attacks.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Ingress filtering, standardized as BCP 38 (RFC 2827), is performed at the gateway to a network and blocks incoming packets whose source address is inside the network.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] This prevents an outside attacker from spoofing the address of an internal machine.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Ideally, the gateway would also perform egress filtering on outgoing packets, which is the blocking of packets from inside the network with a source address that is not inside.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] This prevents an attacker within the network performing filtering from launching IP spoofing attacks against external machines.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] An intrusion detection system (IDS) is a common use of packet filtering, which has been used to secure the environments for sharing data over network and host-based IDS approaches.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] It is also recommended to design network protocols and services so that they do not rely on the source IP address for authentication.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] The CAIDA Spoofer project measures the prevalence of networks that fail to deploy source address validation by inviting volunteers to run a client that attempts to send spoofed packets from their network.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Some upper layer protocols have their own defense against IP spoofing attacks.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] For example, Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) uses sequence numbers negotiated with the remote machine to ensure that arriving packets are part of an established connection.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Since the attacker normally cannot see any reply packets, the sequence number must be guessed in order to hijack the connection.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] The poor implementation in many older operating systems and network devices, however, means that TCP sequence numbers can be predicted.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] The term ***spoofing*** is also sometimes used to refer to *header forgery*, the insertion of false or misleading information in e-mail or netnews headers.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] Falsified headers are used to mislead the recipient or network applications as to the origin of a message.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/ip-address-spoofing] This is a common technique of spammers and sporgers, who wish to conceal the origin of their messages to avoid being tracked.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] The process, which results in the proxy server responding with its own MAC address to an ARP request for a different IP address for proxying purposes, is sometimes referred to as *publishing*.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] The access router gives the dial-up nodes IP addresses in the range 192.168.0.128 – 192.168.0.254; for this example, assume a dial-up node gets IP address 192.168.0.254.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] without being wired into the Ethernet: the access router 'publishes' its own MAC address for 192.168.0.254.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] Now, when another node wired into the Ethernet wants to talk to the dial-up node, it will ask on the network for the MAC address of 192.168.0.254 and find the access router's MAC address.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] It will therefore send its IP packets to the access router, and the access router will know to pass them on to the particular dial-up node.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] All dial-up nodes therefore appear to the wired Ethernet nodes as if they are wired into the same Ethernet subnet.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] Certain applications may require multiple IP addresses on the server.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] Provided the addresses have to be from the 10.0.0.0/24 range, the way the problem is solved is through proxy ARP.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] /other virtual server environments) and 'published' on the 10.0.0.2 interface (although many operating systems allow direct allocation of multiple addresses to one interface, thus eliminating the need for such workarounds).
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] In this scenario a firewall can be configured with a single IP address.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] One simple example of a use for this would be placing a firewall in front of a single host or group of hosts on a subnetwork.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] A proxy ARP firewall can be placed in front of the server.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] In this way the server is put behind a firewall without having to make any further changes to the network.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] Disadvantage of proxy ARP include scalability as ARP resolution by a proxy is required for every device routed in this manner, and reliability, as no fallback mechanism is present, and masquerading can be confusing in some environments.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] Proxy ARP can create DoS attacks on networks if misconfigured.
[src:arp-spoofing-defense/proxy-arp] Proxy ARP can hide device misconfigurations, such as a missing or incorrect default gateway.
